Smart Agriculture Simulation System - AI & IoT Integration
System Overview
A comprehensive smart agriculture platform that combines IoT sensors, AI-powered analytics, and automated control systems to optimize crop yields, reduce resource waste, and enable precision farming.

1. IoT Sensors & Hardware Requirements
A. Environmental Sensors
Soil Monitoring

Soil Moisture Sensors (Capacitive/Resistive)

Purpose: Measure volumetric water content
Placement: Multiple depths (10cm, 30cm, 60cm)
Frequency: Every 15 minutes
Range: 0-100% saturation
Example: DHT22, Capacitive Soil Moisture Sensor v1.2


Soil pH Sensors

Purpose: Monitor soil acidity/alkalinity
Range: pH 3.0-10.0
Frequency: Hourly
Critical for: Nutrient availability optimization


Soil Temperature Sensors (DS18B20)

Purpose: Root zone temperature monitoring
Range: -55°C to +125°C
Frequency: Every 15 minutes
Impact: Germination, growth rates


NPK Sensors (Nitrogen, Phosphorus, Potassium)

Purpose: Soil nutrient level detection
Frequency: Daily
Critical for: Fertilization scheduling


Soil EC Sensors (Electrical Conductivity)

Purpose: Total dissolved salts measurement
Frequency: Hourly
Indicates: Soil salinity and fertilizer concentration



Atmospheric Sensors

Air Temperature & Humidity Sensors (DHT22/SHT31)

Purpose: Ambient climate monitoring
Range: -40°C to +80°C, 0-100% RH
Frequency: Every 5 minutes
Location: 1.5m above crop canopy


Barometric Pressure Sensors (BMP280)

Purpose: Weather prediction
Frequency: Every 10 minutes
Use: Storm forecasting, irrigation timing


Light Intensity Sensors (TSL2561/BH1750)

Purpose: PAR (Photosynthetically Active Radiation)
Range: 0-120,000 lux
Frequency: Continuous during daylight
Impact: Photosynthesis rate estimation


CO2 Sensors (SCD30)

Purpose: Carbon dioxide concentration
Range: 400-10,000 ppm
Frequency: Every 5 minutes
Use: Greenhouse optimization


Wind Speed & Direction (Anemometer)

Purpose: Microclimate monitoring
Frequency: Every 5 minutes
Impact: Evapotranspiration, disease spread



Precipitation Monitoring

Rain Gauge (Tipping Bucket)

Purpose: Precise rainfall measurement
Resolution: 0.2mm per tip
Use: Irrigation adjustment, runoff prediction



B. Plant Health Sensors

Multispectral/Hyperspectral Cameras

Purpose: NDVI (Normalized Difference Vegetation Index)
Bands: Red, NIR, Red Edge
Frequency: Daily or weekly
Detects: Plant stress, disease, nutrient deficiency


Thermal Infrared Cameras

Purpose: Crop water stress detection
Measures: Canopy temperature
Frequency: Midday scans
Use: Precision irrigation targeting


Leaf Wetness Sensors

Purpose: Disease risk assessment
Frequency: Continuous
Impact: Fungal disease prevention



C. Water Management Sensors

Flow Meters

Purpose: Irrigation water volume tracking
Accuracy: ±2%
Location: Main and sub-line pipes


Water Level Sensors (Ultrasonic)

Purpose: Reservoir/tank monitoring
Range: 0-10 meters
Frequency: Continuous


Water Quality Sensors

pH, EC, dissolved oxygen
Purpose: Irrigation water suitability
Frequency: Daily



D. Additional IoT Devices

GPS Trackers (for equipment and drone positioning)
Actuators (solenoid valves, motor controllers)
Gateway Devices (LoRaWAN, NB-IoT, 4G/5G)
Edge Computing Units (Raspberry Pi 4, NVIDIA Jetson Nano)
Weather Stations (integrated multi-sensor units)

E. Sensor Network Architecture
Topology: Star or Mesh network
Communication Protocols:

LoRaWAN (long-range, low-power)
Zigbee (mesh networking)
WiFi (high-bandwidth for cameras)
4G/5G (remote locations)

Power Supply:

Solar panels + battery backup
Ultra-low power design (years of battery life)


2. AI Model for Crop Yield Prediction
A. Model Architecture: Hybrid Deep Learning Ensemble
Primary Model: LSTM-CNN Hybrid Network
Architecture Overview:
Input Layer (Multivariate Time Series)
    ↓
CNN Layers (Feature Extraction)
    ↓
LSTM Layers (Temporal Dependencies)
    ↓
Attention Mechanism
    ↓
Dense Layers
    ↓
Output: Predicted Yield (kg/hectare)
Detailed Architecture:

Input Layer (90 days × 25 features)

Soil moisture (3 depths)
Soil temperature
Air temperature (min, max, avg)
Humidity
Rainfall
Solar radiation
Wind speed
NPK levels
pH, EC
NDVI values
Growth stage indicators
Historical yield data
Crop type (one-hot encoded)


CNN Block (1D Convolution)

Conv1D(64 filters, kernel=3, activation='relu')
BatchNormalization()
MaxPooling1D(pool_size=2)
Conv1D(128 filters, kernel=3, activation='relu')
BatchNormalization()
Purpose: Extract spatial patterns from sensor data


LSTM Block (Sequential Processing)

LSTM(128 units, return_sequences=True)
Dropout(0.3)
LSTM(64 units, return_sequences=True)
Dropout(0.3)
Purpose: Capture temporal dependencies and growth patterns


Attention Layer

Self-attention mechanism
Purpose: Focus on critical growth periods (flowering, fruiting)


Dense Layers (Prediction)

Dense(64, activation='relu')
Dropout(0.2)
Dense(32, activation='relu')
Dense(1, activation='linear')  # Yield output



Loss Function: Huber Loss (robust to outliers)
Optimizer: Adam (learning_rate=0.001)
Metrics: RMSE, MAE, R² score
B. Ensemble Models
Model 1: Random Forest (Baseline)

Input: Aggregated weekly features (mean, max, min, std)
Trees: 500
Max Depth: 20
Purpose: Baseline comparison, feature importance ranking
Advantages: Interpretable, handles missing data well

Model 2: XGBoost

Input: Engineered features + raw sensor data
Boosting Rounds: 1000
Early Stopping: 50 rounds
Purpose: High accuracy, feature interactions
Advantages: Fast training, strong performance

Model 3: Transformer Network

Architecture: Multi-head attention
Purpose: Long-range temporal dependencies
Use Case: Large-scale farms with extensive historical data

C. Feature Engineering
Derived Features:

Growing Degree Days (GDD)
Evapotranspiration (ET₀)
Water Stress Index (CWSI)
Cumulative rainfall
Day length (photoperiod)
Temperature variability
Soil moisture deficit
Nutrient uptake rates
Disease risk scores
Pest pressure indices

Temporal Features:

Days since planting
Days until expected harvest
Growth stage (vegetative, flowering, fruiting)
Season (encoded)
Phenological stages

D. Training Strategy
Dataset Requirements:

Minimum: 3-5 years of historical data
Multiple fields and crop varieties
Include failed and successful seasons
Size: 10,000+ samples per crop type

Data Split:

Training: 70%
Validation: 15%
Testing: 15%
Cross-validation: 5-fold

Training Process:

Data normalization (StandardScaler)
Sequence creation (90-day windows)
Augmentation (synthetic minority oversampling)
Progressive training with curriculum learning
Hyperparameter tuning (Bayesian optimization)

Model Ensemble:

Weighted average of LSTM-CNN (50%), XGBoost (30%), RF (20%)
Weights optimized on validation set

E. Prediction Outputs
Primary Output: Expected yield (kg/hectare)
Confidence Interval: 95% prediction interval
Additional Outputs:

Yield variability map (spatial predictions)
Optimal harvest window (±3 days)
Risk factors (drought, disease, nutrient stress)
Recommended interventions

F. Model Performance Targets

RMSE: <8% of mean yield
MAE: <6% of mean yield
R²: >0.85
Prediction Horizon: 30-90 days before harvest
Update Frequency: Weekly retraining with new sensor data

G. Continuous Learning

Online Learning: Daily model updates with streaming data
Transfer Learning: Adapt models to new crop types
Active Learning: Flag uncertain predictions for human review
A/B Testing: Compare model versions in production

